Colombia Stocks: Canacol, Enka, Mineros, Ecopetrol, Tablemac

-- B y   B l a k e   S c h m i d t
-- 
2011-04-28T20:29:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/colombia-stocks-canacol-enka-mineros-ecopetrol-tablemac.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Bogota trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.  The IGBC Index rose 0.5 percent to 14,300.67, the most in a
week, while the Colcap Index gained 0.4 percent to 1,697.39.  Canacol Energy Ltd. (CNE)  , the Calgary-based  oil
company  that operates fields in  South America , climbed 2.9
percent to 2,330 pesos after raising its 2011 production goal to
10,500 to 11,500 barrels of oil a day. The company’s target had
been 10,000 to 11,000 barrels of oil a day.  Cementos Argos (CEMARGOS CB),  Colombia ’s biggest cement
maker rose 0.8 percent to 10,700 pesos after reporting first-
quarter net income of 29 billion pesos ($16 million) in a
regulatory filing late yesterday. The volume of the company’s
cement sales rose 27 percent from a year earlier to 1.2 million
tons.  Ecopetrol SA (ECOPETL)  , Colombia’s largest oil company,
rose 1.3 percent to 3,850 pesos, its highest level in three
weeks. Finance Minister Juan Carlos Echeverry said the
government seeks to have congress approve by June 20 a plan to
sell up to 10 percent of Ecopetrol’s shares, according to a
statement on the ministry website.  Enka de Colombia SA (ENKA)  , a Medellin-based synthetic
fibers producer, rose 1.5 percent to 13.9 pesos, after the
company said its first-quarter exports rose 33 percent from a
year ago to $17.6 million.  Mineros SA (MINEROS)  , Colombia’s largest gold-mining
company, jumped 1.2 percent to 6,530 pesos, the highest in a
month, after saying it increased production by 49 percent to
28,760 ounces in the first quarter from a year ago.  Tableros y Maderas de Caldas SA (TABLEMA)  , the wood
products maker known as Tablemac, jumped 2.7 percent to 11.6
pesos after the company said first-quarter sales increased 32
percent from a year ago to a record 28 billion pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
